The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems, specifically scheduling problems, and the use of linear programming to solve them. This suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), or cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also discusses lower bounds on the extension complexity of linear programs, which falls under the category of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper presents results on approximation algorithms, which could fall under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
